description: There are reports of Phoradendron bolleanum in area but per Gells et al. 2002 P. bolleanum leaves are densely hairy, plus range restricted to AZ (central, southwestern), NM, Sonora, Chihuahua (page 22 if you want details). But most pics of it on iNaturalist don't show the hair. Calflora database shows the species in Joshua Tree National Park. Leaves in second pic look too fleshy, though. Just doesn't match in nice way. Phoradendron juniperinum is another option, but same paper (p. 25) says that P. juniperinum leaves are "reduced to minute scales". Other sources, pics suggest same thing. So not P. juniperinum. And it's definitely not desert mistletoe, which is in JTNP but only attacks legumes. ... and the botanists at JTNPS also list Phoradendron serotinum subsp. tomentosum as being around. But leaves of mine not hairy. If you have thoughts on the matter, I'd be grateful for ID help.
